Recommendations:
We recommended that management strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE account of the Municipality, specifically, the following:
Local Chief Executive:
To temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee from all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU in due time;
Direct the Property Unit, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to prepare a PIP containing at least the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
The Inventory Committee:
Conduct a complete physical count of PPE based on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Ensure that the physical count is recorded/documented daily in a standard Inventory Count Form (ICF), using the format in Annex A of this Circular, which shall be used as the basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE after the physical count;
Prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) covering all the PPEs of the LGU;
Prepare and update Property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconciled with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the LGU's PPEs;
Property and Accounting Unit
The Property and Accounting Units to undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled. The reconciliation to be completed within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Instruct the BAC and the Municipal Engineer to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion;
Ensure that the Local Development Council, Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time;
The MDC ensure that the projects for inclusion in the 20% DF be predetermined if its charging is within the permissible boundaries of the development fund before it will be considered for appropriation;
Realign or reprogram the unutilized/unimplemented PPAs identified to Priority Development PPAs in accordance with the DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, series of 2020 dated November 4, 2020; and,
Conduct intensive review of the continuing projects funded under the 20% DF to determine if the PPAs are still part of the vital needs of the Municipality, otherwise, reprogram the identified PPAs to priority PPAs.

Recommendation:
We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant monitor and classify expenses properly for smooth determination of the unspent balance for transfer to STF;
The Acting Municipal Treasurer monitor bank accounts movements for early detection of any dormant accounts;
The Municipal Accountant reconcile the balance of the Trust Liability-DRRM with the Cash in Bank 5% DRRM Fund and establish a sufficient cash back-up for the said trust account; and
The Municipal Accountant make disclosure of the unreconciled amount in the Notes to Financial Statement of the Trust Liabilities – DRRM, Cash in Bank 5% DRRM funds and total unutilized balance of the DRRM funds.

Recommendation
We recommended to the GSO the following:
Locate the OR/CRs of the motor vehicles that have no existing OR/CRs in file. If warranted, Management coordinate with the LTO for the issuance of a duplicate OR/CR of the vehicle;
Follow up the OR/CRs of the newly-delivered Rescue Vehicles;
Cause the updating of the registration payments of expired vehicle registrations and ensure annual compliance thereof;
Furthermore, penalties arising from the late registration not be charged against LGU Funds;
Cause the transfer of vehicle registration of the Fire Truck from Mr. Marion A. Cura to LGU Tambulig;
Implement the use of Temporary License Plates for all vehicles in accordance with the specifications laid out under the 2017 LTO Memorandum; and
All of the vehicles be plainly marked “For Official Use Only” and also the name of the department/office such vehicle/s has been issued be indicated to properly identify responsibility on the vehicles used. Furthermore, only the corresponding fuel consumed by vehicles with the required markings will only be allowed in audit.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, and owing to the non-implementation of the project, do the following:
Require the performance of the contractor of its obligation on the contract agreed upon particularly the delivery of the remaining gabions;
Refrain from granting advance payments beyond the limit as allowed by law;
Terminate all MOA with all suppliers, contractors and consultants who are to be tapped in cases of state of emergency and instead determine the capability of these suppliers, contractors, and consultants on a per transaction basis; and
Make the supplier NRMM Construction & Development Corporation refund the excess advance payment made and impose liquidated damages, if warranted.

We recommended the following:

The Inventory Committee conduct complete physical inventory of all property and submit the results thereof to the Agency Auditor; 

The Municipal Treasurer prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report on all unserviceable properties that will be identified during the count and facilitate their immediate disposal to prevent further deterioration and decrease in salvage values; 

The Municipal Accountant make the reconciliation between the results of the physical count and the property records; 

The Municipal Mayor issue an executive order creating an Inventory Committee consistent with COA Circular No. 2020-006 who shall be momentarily relieved of all their regular duties to devote their full time in the conduct of the physical inventory taking until the same is completed.

We recommended the following:

The Inventory Committee conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality and render a Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

The Municipal Treasurer:

Render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map;
Regularly maintain and update the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads; and
Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and

